First of all, I do not recommend using `Map`. It is much better to create a separate class with required fields, let&#39;s call it `EmployeeFilter`.

Then your method should accept this filter and transform it to `Predicate&lt;Employee&gt;` by checking all fields for `null` (it means not filter by this field). If the field is not `null`, then add the given check to the **predicate chain**.

```java
public class Main {

    static class EmployeeFilter {

        private String firstName;
        private String country;

    }

    static class Employee {

        private String firstName;
        private String country;

    }


    public static List&lt;Employee&gt; getEmployeesByFilter(List&lt;Employee&gt; employees, EmployeeFilter filter) {
        return employees.stream()
                        .filter(createPredicate(filter))
                        .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

    private static Predicate&lt;Employee&gt; createPredicate(EmployeeFilter filter) {
        Predicate&lt;Employee&gt; predicate = employee -&gt; true;

        if (filter.firstName != null)
            predicate = predicate.and(employee -&gt; filter.firstName.equals(employee.firstName));
        if (filter.country != null)
            predicate = predicate.and(employee -&gt; filter.country.equals(employee.country));

        return predicate;
    }

}
```

If you need a solution without changing `Employee` you can use reflection:

    import java.beans.IntrospectionException;
    import java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException;
    import java.lang.reflect.Method;
    import java.util.Map;
    import java.util.function.Predicate; 

	public class PredicateBuilder {
	
		private Predicate&lt;Employee&gt; predicate;
		private boolean isError = false;
	
		public PredicateBuilder(Map&lt;String, String&gt; filters ) {
			buildPredicate(filters);
		}
	
		private  void buildPredicate(Map&lt;String, String&gt; filters) {
	
